 reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":5,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":50,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Alice Leynes of Kildare was born in 1332, in Gormanston, County Meath, Ireland. She married Sir William de Loundres Baron Of Naas in 1353, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. She died in Dorset, England."},"et":{"1332–":"1332–Surnud","1330–Male":"1330–Surnud","1354–1383":"1354–1383","1354–Female":"1354–Surnud","1358–1460":"1358–1460","1361–Male":"1361–Surnud","1332–Female":"1332–Surnud","1330":"1330","1361":"1361","1460":"1460","1383":"1383","1382":"1382","1337":"1337","1358":"1358","1332":"1332","1354":"1354","about 1358":"umbes 135